</m:math> shell, what is the spectroscopic notation for this atom?</para></problem></exercise>

    <exercise id="fs-id1412034" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1412035">
        <para id="import-auto-id3043928">(a) If one subshell of an atom has 9 electrons in it, what is the minimum value of <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>l</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{l} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>?  (b) What is the spectroscopic notation for this atom, if this subshell is part of the <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{n=3} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> shell?</para>
    </problem>
<solution id="fs-id1539133">
    <para id="import-auto-id1617226">(a) 2</para>
    <para id="import-auto-id1617228">(b) <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:msup><m:mi>d</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>9</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{3d rSup { size 8{9} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></para></solution>
    </exercise><exercise id="fs-id2683700" type="problems-exercises">
      <problem id="fs-id2683701">
        <para id="import-auto-id1599274">(a) List all possible sets of quantum numbers <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mfenced open="(" close=")"><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mi>,</m:mi><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mi>,</m:mi><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msub><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>l</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mi>,</m:mi><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msub><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mi>s</m:mi></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:mfenced></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:semantics></m:math> for the <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:semantics></m:math> shell, and determine the number of electrons that can be in the shell and each of its subshells.</para><para id="import-auto-id3105697">(b) Show that the number of electrons in the shell equals <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:msup><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{2n rSup { size 8{2} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and that the number in each subshell is <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mfenced open="(" close=")"><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mi>l</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mfenced></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{2 left (2l+1 right )} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para></problem></exercise>

